Church Management & Sacrament System
Architecture, Design & Implementation Document  
Stack: React, Node.js, PostgreSQL, Microservices

1. System overview
A web-based church management system where:

Regular users can:

Login

Register church members

Create sacraments (baptism, first communion, confirmation)

Create & print sacrament cards

View & print member information

Admin-users can:

Do everything a regular user can

Create other admin-users

Create regular users

View church growth charts/analytics

The system is built as microservices behind an API Gateway, with a React frontend and Node.js backend services using PostgreSQL.

2. Requirements
2.1 Functional requirements
Authentication & authorization

User login with email/password

JWT-based session

Roles: ADMIN, USER

Admin can create users and assign roles

Member management

Create, update, view members

Search members by name, ID, and basic filters

View and print member information

Sacrament management

Create sacrament records: baptism, first communion, confirmation

Link sacrament to member

View sacraments per member

Card generation

Generate printable sacrament cards (PDF)

Generate printable member info (PDF)

Analytics

View member growth over time

View sacraments per period

Admin-only dashboard

2.2 Non-functional requirements
Scalability: Each service can scale independently.

Security: JWT, role-based access, HTTPS.

Reliability: Backups, migrations, basic monitoring.

Extensibility: Easy to add new sacraments, roles, or churches.

Performance: Fast search using PostgreSQL indexes.

3. High-level architecture
3.1 Components
Client: React SPA

API Gateway: Node.js (Fastify/Express)

Microservices:

Auth Service

Member Service

Sacrament Service

Document Service

Analytics Service

Databases: One PostgreSQL database per service

(Optional future) Message broker for events

3.2 Request flow
User logs in via React → API Gateway → Auth Service → JWT returned.

React stores JWT (httpOnly cookie or memory).

Subsequent requests include JWT → API Gateway validates → routes to appropriate service.

Services talk only via HTTP (MVP) or events (future).

4. Microservice design
4.1 Auth Service
Responsibilities:

User registration (admin-only)

Login

Role & permission management

Issue & validate JWT (API Gateway validates, service re-checks if needed)

Entities:

users

id (uuid)

church_id (uuid, nullable for super-admin)

name

email (unique)

password_hash

role (ADMIN, USER)

status (ACTIVE, INACTIVE)

created_at, updated_at

churches (for multi-church support)

id (uuid)

name

address

created_at, updated_at

Key endpoints:

POST /auth/login

POST /auth/register (admin-only)

GET /auth/me

POST /auth/logout (optional, for blacklisting)

Implementation notes:

Use bcrypt for password hashing.

Use jsonwebtoken for JWT.

JWT payload: { userId, role, churchId }.

4.2 Member Service
Responsibilities:

Manage church members

Provide data for sacraments, documents, analytics

Entities:

members

id (uuid)

church_id (uuid)

first_name

last_name

middle_name (nullable)

date_of_birth

gender

address

phone

email

status (ACTIVE, INACTIVE, DECEASED)

created_by (user_id)

created_at, updated_at

Indexes:

idx_members_church_name on (church_id, last_name, first_name)

Full-text index on full_name (computed or concatenated)

Key endpoints:

POST /members

GET /members/:id

GET /members?search=&status=&page=&limit=

PUT /members/:id

Implementation notes:

Enforce church_id from JWT, not from client.

Use PostgreSQL full-text search or ILIKE for simple search.

4.3 Sacrament Service
Responsibilities:

Manage sacrament records

Link to members

Provide data for cards and analytics

Entities:

sacrament_types

id (smallint)

code (BAPTISM, FIRST_COMMUNION, CONFIRMATION)

name

Seeded data.

sacraments

id (uuid)

church_id (uuid)

member_id (uuid)

sacrament_type_id (smallint)

date

place

officiant

notes

created_by (user_id)

created_at, updated_at

Key endpoints:

POST /sacraments

GET /sacraments/:id

GET /members/:memberId/sacraments

GET /sacraments?type=&from=&to=&page=&limit=

Implementation notes:

Validate member_id belongs to same church_id as user.

Optionally call Member Service to verify member existence (or cache).

4.4 Document Service
Responsibilities:

Generate PDFs:

Sacrament cards

Member info sheets

Manage templates (basic at first, configurable later)

Entities:

templates

id (uuid)

church_id (uuid)

type (SACRAMENT_CARD, MEMBER_INFO)

name

content (HTML or template string)

created_at, updated_at

Key endpoints:

POST /documents/sacrament-card

Body: { memberId, sacramentId }

Returns: PDF stream or URL

POST /documents/member-info

Body: { memberId }

Returns: PDF stream or URL

Implementation notes:

Use puppeteer to render HTML templates to PDF, or pdfkit.

Fetch member & sacrament data from respective services.

For performance, offload heavy PDF generation to a job queue (BullMQ + Redis).

4.5 Analytics Service
Responsibilities:

Provide church growth and sacrament statistics

Admin-only dashboards

Data model (MVP):

No separate tables initially; query Member & Sacrament services directly and cache results in:

analytics_cache

id (uuid)

church_id

metric_key (e.g., members_growth_monthly)

data (JSON)

generated_at

Key endpoints:

GET /analytics/members/growth?from=&to=

GET /analytics/sacraments/count?groupBy=month

GET /analytics/dashboard

Implementation notes:

MVP: call Member/Sacrament services, aggregate in memory, cache.

Future: switch to event-driven and maintain precomputed aggregates.

5. API Gateway design
Responsibilities:

Route requests to services

Validate JWT

Enforce basic role checks

Centralized logging, rate limiting, CORS

Routing examples:

/auth/* → Auth Service

/members/* → Member Service

/sacraments/* → Sacrament Service

/documents/* → Document Service

/analytics/* → Analytics Service

Implementation notes:

Node.js + Fastify/Express

Middleware:

authMiddleware to verify JWT and attach req.user

roleMiddleware(requiredRole) for admin-only routes

Use environment variables for service URLs.

6. Frontend (React) design
6.1 Structure
State management: React Query for server state, minimal local state.

Routing: React Router.

UI: TailwindCSS or component library.

